<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>Spanish - Gu&#237;a para Localizaci&#243;n de Fallas del Sistema El&#233;ctrico - 3200, 4200, 4300, 4400,
        7300, 7400, 7500, 8500, 8600 - STEERING COLUMN ASSEMBLY, STANDARD - 5000, 9000 CONV. - DISASSEMBLE AND ASSEMBLE
        - UNIVERSAL JOINTS
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="disassemble" graphiccount="6">
        <title>UNIVERSAL JOINTS</title>
        <svcprocinfo>
            <para>The universal joints at the steering gear may be removed and serviced separately. To service the upper
                universal joint, it is necessary to remove the steering column. Refer to
                <hotlnk document="s05011_6.xml" xrefid="hl0501103">REMOVE AND INSTALL, STEERING COLUMN
                    <xref refid="hl0501103"/>
                </hotlnk>
                .
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Do not damage the bearing surfaces.</para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Disassemble</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Place the universal joint in a vise (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501106">Figure 6</hotlnk>). Remove the snap ring fitting in the grooves of the
                    spider bearings which locate them on the inside of the yokes.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0501106" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0501106" filename="../figg05/G0501106.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6. Snap Ring Removal</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. BEARING</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. YOKE</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. SPIDER</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. SNAP RING</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Move the shaft assembly in the vise with one shaft clamped firmly in the vise with the
                    yoke free and the other yoke suspended with the bearing to be removed facing down (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501107">Figure 7</hotlnk>). Tap yoke beside the bearing to be removed; the bearing
                    should walk out of the yoke.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0501107" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0501107" filename="../figg05/G0501107.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7. Bearing Removal</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. BEARING</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. YOKE</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If the bearing does not come completely out, clamp the bearing in a vise.
                    <emph type="bold">Use copper jaw covers on the vise</emph>. Strike the yoke with a soft hammer and
                    drive the yoke away from the bearing (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501108">Figure 8</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0501108" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0501108" filename="../figg05/G0501108.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 8. Bearing Removal</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. YOKE</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. BEARING</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Assemble</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Make certain parts are clean before assembly.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Rest the yoke on a hard surface. Tap one bearing part way into the yoke with a soft
                    hammer (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501109">Figure 9</hotlnk>). Be certain that the bearings are started straight into
                    the yoke.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0501109" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0501109" filename="../figg05/G0501109.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 9. Install Bearing Part Way into the Yoke</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. YOKE</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. BEARING</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Insert the spider through the opposite empty bearing hole. Swing the spider into place
                    and down into the partially installed bearing.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Turn the assembly over and tap the opposite bearing part way into the yoke. Be certain
                    that the bearing is straight in the yoke.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Place the yoke in the vise with the bearings against the vise jaws. Tighten the vise
                    slowly and the bearings will be pressed into the yoke (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501110">Figure 10</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0501110" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0501110" filename="../figg05/G0501110.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 10. Press Bearings into Yoke</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. YOKE</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. SPIDER</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. YOKE</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. BEARING</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After pressing the bearings into the yoke, the spider may be off center in the yoke.
                    This is desirable since it permits installation of the snap ring on the side with the most
                    clearance. Install the snap ring (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501111">Figure 11</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0501111" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0501111" filename="../figg05/G0501111.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 11. Snap Ring Installation</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. GREASE FITTING</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. SNAP RING</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. YOKE</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With the first snap ring in place, turn the assembly over. The bearing with the snap
                    ring installed should be on the bottom. Rest the yoke on the vise and strike the top bearing with a
                    soft hammer. This will seat both bearings. Snap rings should rest against the inside milled surface
                    of the yoke. Install the remaining snap ring.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Lubricate the universal joint with Fleetrite EP2 moly grease or equivalent NLGI #2
                    lithium grease.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After the bearings are installed and lubricated, they must move freely. If tight, tap
                    the yoke with a soft hammer until the bearings are free.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
